10 Before You Go
You are almost there! ⚙️
Today you:

prepared one cleaned app dataset;
built zone, efficiency and action-family views;
added headline value boxes with AD -&gt; Luka deltas;
used page_sidebar(), card(), navset_card_tab(), value_box() and layout_columns();
polished the dashboard with a consistent Lakers theme.

Next week we shift from building the dashboard to sharing it — deployment, GitHub Pages and the final portfolio presentation.

1 Recap: Last Week
Before we dive in, let’s quickly review what we set up last week:

R, RStudio and Git are installed and working;
the nba-analytics RStudio project exists with folders data/raw/, data/cleaned/, scripts/, output/ and app/;
the project is connected to a GitHub repository;
you made and pushed your first commit.







If anything from last week is incomplete, go back to Workbook 1 and finish the setup before continuing.

9 Before You Go
Nice work! 🏀
Today you:

sourced real NBA data through an API-based workflow;
learned how to read package documentation to choose the right parameters;
inspected and cleaned raw team and player tables;
built reusable season-level datasets;
saved raw API pulls in data/raw/ and cleaned files in data/cleaned/.

Next week we will turn these saved basketball datasets into clear charts, add simple Plotly interactivity, and build the first version of the dashboard app.

2 Why This Matters
Analysts do not work in isolated scripts. They work in projects that need to be:

reproducible;
easy to revisit;
easy to share;
easy to extend into reports, dashboards and published outputs.

Git and GitHub are therefore part of the analytical workflow, not an optional extra.

3 Pre-Class Checklist
Before the seminar, make sure that:

R 4.5 or later is installed;
RStudio opens normally;
Git is installed on your machine [link];
in RStudio, Tools -&gt; Global Options -&gt; Git/SVN shows a detected Git executable;
you have a GitHub account;
you can access the internet from your machine.







As a student, you can apply to GitHub Education. Follow the application steps at this link: [link]. This will grant you access to additional features that may become useful later in the module.

7 Before You Go
Well done for getting through to the end! 🚀
Today you:

installed the course package stack;
created the shared project structure;
connected the project to GitHub;
made the first public commit.

Next week we will use hoopR to source real NBA data, inspect it, and save cleaned datasets for later visualisation and dashboard work.

5 Independent Practice
Try these small extensions:

change the selected player to someone else and re-run the app;
swap share for the raw attempt count (n) on the y-axis, and compare what the two versions emphasise;
compute FG% per zone instead of share — rebuild the pre-aggregation step from lakers_shots using summarise(fg_pct = mean(shot_made_flag)), save that as a new RDS and plot it;
add a checkboxInput in the UI called "made_only" — you will need to rebuild the pre-aggregation with a made flag so the app can switch between “all shots” and “made only”;
change the colour palette and the title to match a different team.

7 Before You Go
Great work! ✨
Today you:

started from a cleaned .rds file of Lakers shots across four regular seasons;
split those seasons into an AD Era and a Luka Era around the 1 February 2025 trade;
built a static bar chart comparing a player’s shot distribution across zones;
converted the chart into a Plotly chart with hover text;
pre-aggregated the data into a 60-row shot_zones.rds so the Shiny app stays lightweight;
built a first Shiny app in four small stages — minimal, with a selector, with a layout, and finally with Plotly inside Shiny.

Next week we will turn this app into a more polished dashboard with a richer layout, additional charts and a short automatic commentary panel.
